  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN240">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>āṭunaṭaip puraviyuṅ kaḷiṟun tērum</l>
<l>vāṭā yāṇar nāṭu mūrum</l>
<l>pāṭunark karukā vāa yaṇṭiraṉ</l>
<l>kōṭēn talkuṟ kuṟuntoṭi makaḷiroṭu</l>
<l>kāla ṉeṉṉuṅ kaṇṇili yuyppa</l>
<l>mēlō rulaka meytiṉa ṉeṉāap</l>
<l>potta vaṟaiyuṭ pōḻvāyk kūkai</l>
<l>cuṭṭuk kuviyeṉac cettōrp payiruṅ</l>
<l>kaḷḷiyam paṟantalai voruciṟai yalki</l>
<l>yoḷḷeri naippa vuṭampu māyantatu</l>
<l>pulleṉ kaṇṇar puravalark kāṇātu</l>
<l>kalleṉ cuṟṟamoṭu kaiyaḻintu pulavar</l>
<l>vāṭiya paciya rākippiṟar</l>
<l>nāṭupaṭu celaviṉa rāyiṉa riṉiyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“Āay Aṇṭiraṉ who was not scarce to singers (3)</l>
<l>with horses with prancing gait, elephants bulle, chariots, (1)</l>
<l>lands of unfading fertility and villages, (2)</l>
<l>when the eyeless man called Kālaṉ sent him (5)</l>
<l>along with [his] women with hips eminent in [their] curves [and] small bracelets, (4)</l>
<l>he reached the world of those above,” so thinking, (6)</l>
<l>staying on one side of the spurge waste land (9)</l>
<l> where owls with cleft beaks call the dead: </l>
<l>“heap [them] after burning in the hollow chamber”, (7f.)</l>
<l>[his] body vanished when the bright flames burned [it]. (10) </l>
<l> The poets, (12d)</l>
<l> with empty eyes, not seeing a protector (11)</l>
<l>desolate along with [their] noisy retinue, (12a-c)</l>
<l>being faded from hunger (13a-c)</l>
<l>they now have become people who go to face the lands of others. (13c-14)    </l>     
</lg>
